144
15:23.250 --> 15:31.650
And with that notation now in our hands, let's return to the discussion
of classical information and probabilistic states, in particular.

145
15:31.650 --> 15:38.490
And let's consider what happens
when we measure a system while it's in some probabilistic state.

146
15:38.490 --> 15:45.750
We might not ordinarily
refer to a measurement or the act of measuring
something in a classical setting, but the term makes sense.

147
15:45.750 --> 15:55.230
In essence, when we talk
about measuring the system X in this context, we just mean that we look at it and we recognize whatever state it's in.

148
15:55.230 --> 16:02.130
Of course, when we look at the system, we don't see a probabilistic state, we see a classical state,

149
16:02.130 --> 16:08.970
and the particular
classical state that we see is one that we can
imagine is chosen randomly according to the probabilities.

150
16:08.970 --> 16:16.200
Now, you might object on
philosophical grounds to the idea that the classical state we see is somehow chosen at random

151
16:16.200 --> 16:23.490
at the moment that we measure or we look at the system, the system simply was in some particular
classical state all along

152
16:23.490 --> 16:31.140
and we just happen to have
learned what the state was, but for the sake of thinking about the mathematical
framework we're working with,

153
16:31.140 --> 16:39.300
it's okay to think about it this way and doing so will allow us to draw a parallel with
quantum information a little bit later.

154
16:39.300 --> 16:46.860
Let's suppose that the
classical state that we see is the classical state a, which could be any state in our set sigma.

155
16:46.860 --> 16:52.680
This changes the probabilistic
state of X in general, at least from our point of view.

156
16:52.680 --> 16:58.440
The probabilities no longer
have any significance because we now know what
the classical state of X is.

157
16:58.440 --> 17:03.060
It's a, and there's no longer
any uncertainty about this.

158
17:03.060 --> 17:10.410
So we would now say this
that the probability that the system is in the state a is one.

159
17:10.410 --> 17:18.990
We know this because we just looked at it and we saw that the classical state is a, so the new probabilistic state of X is one

160
17:18.990 --> 17:24.690
in which the probability of
being in the classical state a is equal to one.

161
17:24.690 --> 17:29.790
And that probabilistic state is represented by the
probability vector ket a.

162
17:29.790 --> 17:36.120
We have a one in the entry corresponding to the classical state a and a zero in all other entries.

163
17:36.120 --> 17:43.920
For example, if we again
consider the situation where X is a bit and we have the same
probabilistic state as before,

164
17:43.920 --> 17:50.310
then if we measure X, we can imagine that a
transition takes place.

165
17:50.310 --> 17:59.490
With probability three quarters, we see the classical state zero, and by measuring, we transition to ket zero
being our probabilistic state,

166
17:59.490 --> 18:04.440
and with probability one quarter, we transition to ket one.

167
18:04.440 --> 18:10.800
You can think about this as a transition of knowledge if you prefer as opposed to an actual
physical transition,

168
18:10.800 --> 18:16.230
but what's important for
the sake of this lesson is to recognize how the mathematics works.

169
18:16.230 --> 18:22.350
It's kind of trivial actually, but by recognizing this triviality, the analogous description
for the quantum setting

170
18:22.350 --> 18:26.400
might seem a little bit less mysterious.

171
18:26.400 --> 18:33.180
One final note is that to another person who didn't happen to see what
the classical state of X was when we measured it,

172
18:33.180 --> 18:38.820
the probabilistic state
naturally wouldn't change as a result of us having measured it.

173
18:38.820 --> 18:46.680
That's okay. Different individuals can
have different knowledge of a particular system and correspondingly choose
different probabilistic states

174
18:46.680 --> 18:50.310
to represent their
knowledge of that system.

175
18:50.310 --> 18:57.900
In the last part of this discussion of classical information, we'll talk about classical operations that can be performed on a system,

176
18:57.900 --> 19:01.680
starting with deterministic operations.

177
19:01.680 --> 19:09.390
When we perform an operation on a system, its state generally changes as a result, and in this context, the word deterministic means

178
19:09.390 --> 19:15.900
that the result of performing
the operation depends entirely on whatever classical
state the system was in

179
19:15.900 --> 19:19.680
prior to the operation being performed.

180
19:19.680 --> 19:28.830
In other words, there's
no element of chance when a deterministic
operation is performed, so there's no randomness
or uncertainty involved.

181
19:28.830 --> 19:34.080
In mathematical terms, deterministic operations
are described by functions.

182
19:34.080 --> 19:40.950
Every function f of the form
that you see right here, which means that both the input and the output of the function

183
19:40.950 --> 19:46.890
correspond to elements of
our classical state set sigma describes a deterministic operation.

184
19:46.890 --> 19:53.280
The classical state a is
transformed into the state f of a for each choice of a state a.

185
19:53.280 --> 20:00.777
For every function f of this form, there will always be a unique matrix M satisfying this condition
that you see right here,

186
20:00.777 --> 20:08.040
and that is that by multiplying
M to the vector ket a gives us the vector ket f of a,

187
20:08.040 --> 20:11.640
and that's true for every
choice of a classical state a.

188
20:11.640 --> 20:17.550
It's not too hard to write down
an explicit description of M given whatever function f
of this form we've chosen.

189
20:17.550 --> 20:22.890
It will always have exactly
one, one in each column with every other entry equal to zero.

190
20:22.890 --> 20:30.360
And here's the formula. The b, a entry of M is equal to one if b is equal to f of a

191
20:30.360 --> 20:37.950
and otherwise, it's equal to zero, and by this, we mean
this is the entry of M whose row corresponds to b

192
20:37.950 --> 20:41.430
and whose column corresponds to a.

